content.content:
# Using @theme in Tailwind CSS v4

## Overview

The `@theme` directive enables you to define CSS custom properties that automatically generate corresponding utility classes in Tailwind CSS v4.

## Basic Syntax

Define theme variables at the top level of your CSS file:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  --color-mint-500: oklch(0.72 0.11 178);
}
```

This creates utility classes like `bg-mint-500`, `text-mint-500`, and `fill-mint-500` automatically.

## Key Benefits

According to the documentation: "Theme variables are special CSS variables defined using the `@theme` directive that influence which utility classes exist in your project."

Rather than using arbitrary values with `bg-[var(--color-primary-500)]`, you can leverage native utility classes generated from theme variables.

## Common Use Cases

**Extending the default theme:**
```css
@theme {
  --font-script: Great Vibes, cursive;
}
```

**Overriding defaults:**
```css
@theme {
  --breakpoint-sm: 30rem;
}
```

**Complete theme replacement:**
```css
@theme {
  --*: initial;
  --color-primary: #3f3cbb;
}
```

## Theme Variable Namespaces

Theme variables organize into namespaces that map to specific utilities:
- `--color-*` → color utilities
- `--font-*` → font families
- `--text-*` → font sizes
- `--spacing-*` → padding, margins, sizing
- `--breakpoint-*` → responsive variants

The directive makes design tokens first-class framework citizens rather than just CSS variables.

